CAL RIPKEN JR.was baseball's premier shortstop in the 80s.Despite already
logging nine seasons in the Major Leagues, RIPKEN is only 29 years old,He
Still has many more seasons to fortify his impressive credentials and further
strengthen his candidacy for baseball's Hall of Fame
RIPKEN was the 1982 American League Rookie of the Year, beating out both
WADE BOGGS and KENT HRBEK. On May 30, 1982, RIPKEN started a game
for the Orioles at third base. He has not missed a game since. His iron-man streak
now stands at 1,250 consecutive games played. That is the third longest such
streak in baseball history, Only LOU GEHRIG (2,130) and EVERETT SCOTT (1,307)
had longer streaks, RIPKEN enjoyed his best season in 1983 when he led lthe
Orioles to the World Series title. He batted .318 that season with 211 hits. 27
home runs, 102 RBIs, 47 doubles and 121 runs scored. He was named the 1983
IN 1989, RIPKEN was the most important player on an Orioles team that
shocked the baseball world by rebounding from a horrendous 1988 season to
win 87 games and finish a very strong second in the AL East. He hit 21 home
runs and drove in 93 runs. His 21 home runs marked the eighth consecutive
season that he had 20 or more home runs. That is a record for shortstops.
RIPKEN had an outstanding year in the field, committing a career low 8 errors
He led AL shortstops with 119 double plays turned. His .990 fielding percen-
tage was the best of his career.
